text: Immunodeficiency 60, also known as BACH2-related immunodeficiency and autoimmunity, is a type of combined T cell and B cell immunodeficiency. It is characterized by variably decreased immunoglobulin production, decreased T-regulatory cells, overall impaired lymphocyte maturation, inflammatory bowel disease, and recurrent sinopulmonary infections. The condition has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the BACH2 gene on chromosome 6q15. It is also known as IMD60.

I understand that you are seeking information about immunodeficiency 27a, which is a type of primary immunodeficiency disease. Immunodeficiency 27a has a genetic basis and is characterized by high levels of interferon gamma (IFNG) in the blood, an impaired cellular response to IFNG, and early and often fatal mycobacterial infections. It is caused by mutations in the IFNGR1 gene on chromosome 6q23.3. This condition is also known as autosomal recessive IFN-gamma receptor 1 deficiency or autosomal recessive immunodeficiency 27A, mycobacteriosis.

That is correct. Immunodeficiency 27b, also known as autosomal dominant IFNGR1 deficiency or MSMD due to partial IFNgammaR1 deficiency, is a type of primary immunodeficiency disease characterized by residual cellular responses to IFNG in vitro and recurrent, moderately severe infections with environmental mycobacteria or bacillus Calmette-Guerin that has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the IFNGR1 gene on chromosome 6q23.3. It is also known by other synonyms such as autosomal dominant immunodeficiency 27B, mycobacteriosis or autosomal dominant mendelian susceptibility to mycobacterial diseases due to partial IFNgammaR1 deficiency.

Here are some alternative ways to rephrase the statement:

* Immune deficiency 11a is a genetic disorder that affects the body's immune system.
* It is characterized by a weakened immune system, which makes it difficult for the body to fight off infections and diseases.
* The condition results from mutations in the CARD11 gene on chromosome 7p22.2, leading to defective intracellular signaling in T and B cells and other issues with the immune system.
* Immune deficiency 11a is a severe form of combined immunodeficiency that can cause a range of health problems if left untreated.
* This type of immune deficiency has a recessive inheritance pattern, meaning it only develops when both copies of the gene are affected.

Immunodeficiency 11b, also known as IMD11B, is a type of T cell deficiency characterized by defects in T-cell activation, increased IgE, eosinophilia and early childhood onset of moderate to severe atopic dermatitis. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the CARD11 gene on chromosome 7p22.2. The exact synonyms for this condition include atopic dermatitis, elevated IgE and eosinophilia, and immunodeficiency 11B with atopic dermatitis.

Immunodeficiency 15b, also known as IMD15B, is a severe combined immunodeficiency characterized by life-threatening infections caused by bacteria, fungi, and viruses. It typically affects infants and leads to failure to thrive, impaired differentiation and activation of immune cells, hypo or agammaglobulinemia (low levels of immunoglobulins), and normal B and T cell numbers. The condition is caused by mutations in the IKBKB gene on chromosome 8p11.21.

immunodeficiency 15a is a type of autosomal dominant disease characterized by combined T cell and B cell immunodeficiency, inflammation, and epithelial defects. It has a material basis in heterozygous missense mutation in the IKBKB gene on chromosome 8p11.21.

The immunodeficiency 26, also known as IMD26 or SCID due to DNA-PKcs deficiency, is a severe combined immunodeficiency characterized by a lack of peripheral B and T cells but normal numbers of NK cells. It also presents with a complete block in B-cell differentiation and a defect in slow repair of DNA double-strand breaks in fibroblasts. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the PRKDC gene on chromosome 8q11.21.

That is correct, combined immunodeficiency (CID) is a type of primary immune deficiency disease that affects the immune system in multiple ways. It can result from mutations or defects in several genes involved in the development and functioning of the immune system. These genetic defects can lead to problems with the production of antibodies, a weakened immune response to infections, and an increased susceptibility to illness and infection. CID is often diagnosed in infancy or early childhood and can affect individuals differently depending on which genes are affected. Treatment for CID typically involves regular medical care, vaccinations, and sometimes medications to help boost the immune system.

Dendritic cell deficiency is a type of primary immunodeficiency disease characterized by impaired function or reduced numbers of dendritic cells. Dendritic cells are important for the development and activation of T-cells, which play a crucial role in the immune system. When someone has dendritic cell deficiency, their immune system may not be able to properly respond to infections and other foreign substances. This can make them more susceptible to illness and disease. Treatment options for dendritic cell deficiency may include immunoglobulin replacement therapy, stem cell transplantation, or other medications to help support the immune system. It is important to consult with a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment of this condition.

That's correct! B cell and dendritic cell deficiency is a type of combined immunodeficiency characterized by impaired function or reduced numbers of dendritic cells and B cells. Is there anything else you would like to know about this topic?
t cell b cell and nk cell deficiency is a type of combined immunodeficiency, which is characterized by impaired function or reduced numbers of T cells, B cells, and natural killer (NK) cells.

monocyte dendritic cell and nk cell deficiency is a type of combined immunodeficiency.
monocyte dendritic cell and nk cell deficiency has the definition: A combined immunodeficiency characterized by impaired function or reduced numbers of monocytes, dendritic cells, and natural killer (NK) cells.

The term "immunodeficiency 54" refers to a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by severe intra- and extrauterine growth retardation, microcephaly, decreased numbers of CD56(dim) natural killer cells, adrenal insufficiency, and recurrent viral infections. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the MCM4 gene on chromosome 8q11.21. It is also known as IMD54, NKCD, familial isolated natural killer cell deficiency, primary immunodeficiency due to MCM4 deficiency, and primary immunodeficiency with natural-killer cell deficiency and adrenal insufficiency.

immunodeficiency 41 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which means that it is passed down through families in an inherited pattern where the gene for the disease is located on one of the non-sex chromosones (autosomes). It is characterized by a defect in T cell regulation with proliferation of CD8+ T cells, impaired antibody specific responses, and elevated cytokines resulting in recurrent viral, fungal, and bacterial infections, lymphadenopathy, and variable autoimmune features. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the IL2RA gene on chromosome 10p15.1.

IMD39, also known as Immunodeficiency 39, is a type of primary immunodeficiency disease. It is characterized by impaired interferon I and III production in response to influenza virus infection and has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the IRF7 gene on chromosome 11p15.5.<|end

Immunodeficiency 10, also known as IMD10 or CID due to STIM1 deficiency, is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the T and NK cells of the immune system. It causes recurrent infections in childhood due to defective T- and NK-cell function with a material basis in homozygous mutation in the STIM1 gene on chromosome 11p15.4. This condition has exact synonyms such as STIM1 deficiency, IMD10, combined immunodeficiency due to STIM1 deficiency, and immune dysfunction with T-cell inactivation due to calcium entry defect 2.

User, you are correct. Immunodeficiency 18, also known as CD3-epsilon deficiency or IMD18, is a type of primary immunodeficiency disease that has a genetic basis and is characterized by the absence or dysfunction of the CD3E gene on chromosome 11q23.3. This leads to recurrent infections with variable severity in infants and young children. It is an autosomal recessive disease, which means that it requires the inheritance of two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) for its development.

Immunodeficiency 19, also known as SCID T cell-negative, B cell-positive, NK cell-positive, is a severe combined immunodeficiency that affects the body's ability to fight infections. It is caused by mutations in the CD3D gene on chromosome 11q23.3 and results in a lack of T cells, B cells, and natural killer cells. This condition typically presents in early infancy with recurrent bacterial, viral, and fungal infections. It has an autosomal recessive inheritance pattern, which means that it can be passed down through families.

Immunodeficiency 17, also known as CD3-gamma deficiency or IMD17, is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by partial T-cell lymphopenia with normal numbers of B and NK cells. It has a highly variable clinical severity and can have a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the CD3G gene on chromosome 11q23.3.

Immunodeficiency 59, also known as IMD59 or granulocytopenia with immunoglobin abnormality, is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the body's ability to produce certain types of white blood cells, specifically B-cells and dendritic cells. This deficiency can lead to recurrent infections in various parts of the body such as the respiratory tract, skin, and mucous membranes. Additionally, individuals with this condition may experience stress-induced hypoglycemia. Immunodeficiency 59 is caused by mutations in the HYOU1 gene located on chromosome 11q23.3.

IMD44 is a primary immunodeficiency disease characterized by increased susceptibility to viral infections and adverse multisystemic reaction to vaccination with apparent defects in mitochondrial fission and fusion that has material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the STAT2 gene on chromosome 12q13.3.

Immunodeficiency 9, also known as CID due to ORAI1 deficiency or IMD9, is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by early onset of recurrent infections, ectodermal dysplasia, and congenital myopathy. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ORAI1 gene, which encodes a subunit of the plasma membrane calcium channel CRAC on chromosome 12q24.31.<|end

I'm sorry, but I am not programmed to provide information on specific medical conditions or diseases. However, I can tell you that immunodeficiency 7, also known as TCR-alpha/beta deficient, is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by a T cell deficiency with decreased or absent CD3+ T cells and TCR-alpha/beta expression. This condition can result in recurrent infections, immune dysregulation, and failure to thrive, particularly in children. It is caused by mutations in the TRAC gene on chromosome 14q11.2.

Immune Deficiency 65 (IMD65) is a type of primary immunodeficiency disease that primarily affects infants. It is characterized by recurrent and severe viral infections, impaired cellular type I interferon response, and poor outcomes after vaccination with live attenuated vaccines. The disease has a genetic basis, with mutations in the IRF9 gene on chromosome 14q12 being the most common cause. It is also known as IMD65 or immunodeficiency 65, susceptibility to viral infections.

Immunodeficiency 64, also known as IMD64, is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by T cell, B cell, and NK cell deficiency. This condition presents with recurrent bacterial, viral, and fungal infections in early childhood due to decreased phosphorylation of the extracellular-signal-regulated serine kinase ERK in T and B cells. The RASGRP1 gene on chromosome 15q14 is responsible for this condition when it is homozygous or compound heterozygous.

Immunodeficiency 43, also known as B2M deficiency or IMD43, is a type of primary immunodeficiency disease. It is characterized by recurrent infections, reduced serum concentrations of immunoglobulin G and albumin due to rapid degradation of these proteins, abnormal renal or liver function, and excessive gastrointestinal protein that has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the B2M gene on chromosome 15q21.1.<|end_of_tool_paragraph|>

The term "immunodeficiency 56" refers to a type of combined T cell and B cell immunodeficiency that is characterized by defects in both class-switched B cells and T-cell responses. This condition has a material basis in mutations in the IL21R gene on chromosome 16p12.1, which can result in homozygous or compound heterozygous inheritance. The exact synonyms for this condition include IL21R immunodeficiency, IMD56, and combined immunodeficiency due to IL21R deficiency.

Immunodeficiency 52, also known as IMD52 or severe combined immunodeficiency due to LAT deficiency, is a type of autosomal recessive disease that presents with onset of severe recurrent infections in infancy. It is characterized by a defect in T-cell receptor signaling and has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in LAT on chromosome 16p11.2.

Immune deficiency 58, also known as IMD58, is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the immune system. It is characterized by defective T-cell function with decreased Treg cells and deficient CD3/CD28 costimulation responses in both CD4+ and CD8+ T cells, variable impairment in B-cell function, early-onset skin lesions, recurrent respiratory infections or allergies, and chronic persistent infections that have a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the CARMIL2 gene on chromosome 16q22.1.

Immunodeficiency 32B, also known as IRF8-deficient immunodeficiency, is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the development or function of monocytes, dendritic cells, and natural killer (NK) cells. These cells play a vital role in the immune system and help to protect the body against infections. When these cells are not functioning properly due to genetic mutations, individuals with 32B are at an increased risk of developing recurrent viral infections, particularly during childhood. The condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the IRF8 gene on chromosome 16q24.1. It is important to note that there are other genetic factors that can also contribute to the development of immunodeficiency in some individuals, and a thorough evaluation by a qualified medical professional is necessary for an accurate diagnosis and appropriate treatment plan.

Immunodeficiency 32a, also known as IMD32A or MSMD, is a type of autosomal dominant disease characterized by dendritic cell deficiency and increased susceptibility to mycobacterial infections. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the IRF8 gene on chromosome 16q24.1. This condition is also known as Mendelian susceptibility to mycobacterial diseases due to partial IRF8 deficiency or MSMD due to partial interferon regulatory factor 8 deficiency. It has an exact synonym of immunodeficiency 32a, mycobacteriosis, autosomal dominant.

Immunodeficiency 13 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, also known as ICL or IMD13. It is characterized by decreased CD4 T-lymphocyte counts and has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the UNC119 gene on chromosome 17q11.2. This condition is also known as idiopathic CD4 lymphopenia, which means that the exact cause of the disease is not yet known.

Immunodeficiency 12, also known as IMD12, is a type of combined immunodeficiency characterized by decreased titers of specific antibodies and impaired T cells proliferative responses to mitogens. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the MALT1 gene on chromosome 18q21.32. The term "immunodeficiency" refers to a deficiency in the immune system, which can result in an increased susceptibility to infections and other diseases. Combined immunodeficiency refers to a condition where multiple aspects of the immune system are affected. MALT1 (Mucosa-Associated Lymphoid Tissue Transcription Factor 1) is a gene that plays a role in regulating the development and function of immune cells. A mutation in this gene can result in impaired immune function, leading to an increased risk of infections and other related health problems. IMD12 is one such example of a combined immunodeficiency disorder caused by MALT1 gene mutations.

Immunodeficiency 35, also known as IMD35 or TYK2 deficiency, is a type of primary immunodeficiency disease that is characterized by increased susceptibility to mycobacterial infections after BCG vaccination and impaired cellular responses to certain cytokines, including IL-12, IFN-alpha/beta, IL-23, and IL-10. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the TYK2 gene on chromosome 19p13.2.

Immunodeficiency 30 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, characterized by the absence of responses to IL12 and IL23 in T cells and NK cells. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the IL12RB1 gene on chromosome 19p13.11. It is also known as IMD30, MSMD due to complete IL12RB1 deficiency, Mendelian susceptibility to interleukin 12 receptor beta 1 deficiency and Mendelian susceptibility to mycobacterial diseases due to complete IL12RB1 deficiency.

IMD62, also known as immunodeficiency 62, is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by B cell deficiency and recurrent infections. It has a material basis in mutations in the ARHGEF1 gene on chromosome 19q13.2. The condition is defined as having low levels of circulating memory B cells and almost undetectable antibodies, with onset typically occurring in the first decade of life. IMD62 has the exact synonym of immunodeficiency 62.

IMD53, also known as combined T cell and B cell immunodeficiency 53, is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by recurrent upper and lower respiratory infections, an increase in the CD4+ T cell to CD8+ T cell ratio, impaired T-cell proliferative responses to multiple antigens, and an impaired ability to produce specific immunoglobulins. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the RELB gene on chromosome 19q13.32.

Immunodeficiency 55, also known as IMD55 or combined immunodeficiency due to GINS1 deficiency, is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by intrauterine growth retardation and a defect in DNA replication causing impaired immune cell differentiation in the bone marrow resulting in natural killer cell deficiency and chronic neutropenia. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the GINS1 gene on chromosome 20p11.21.<|end

IMD45 is a type of primary immunodeficiency disease characterized by impaired control the replication of certain viruses and failure to develop an antiviral state in response to alpha-interferon or beta-interferon that has_material_basis_in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the IFNAR2 gene on chromosome 21q22.11.

The term "immunodeficiency 28" refers to a type of primary immunodeficiency disease that is characterized by increased susceptibility to mycobacterial disease, high levels of IFNG in the plasma, and absence of cellular response to IFNG that has material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the IFNGR2 gene on chromosome 21q22.11. It is also known as IFNGR2 deficiency, IMD28, MSMD due to complete IFNgammaR2 deficiency, Mendelian susceptibility to mycobacterial diseases due to complete IFNgammaR2 deficiency, and immunodeficiency 28, mycobacteriosis.

Immunodeficiency 51, also known as CANDF5 and IMD51, is a type of primary immunodeficiency disease. It is characterized by chronic mucocutaneous candidiasis in the first years of life and a lack of cellular responses to certain IL17 isoforms due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the IL17RA gene on chromosome 22q11.1.<|end

The immunodeficiency condition referred to as 63 is a type of autosomal recessive disease. It affects the T cell and NK cell components of the immune system, resulting in impaired differentiation of NK cells, abnormalities in T cell function, recurrent infections, hypergammaglobulinemia, lymphoid proliferation, dermatitis, enteropathy, and other issues. It is caused by mutations in the IL2RB gene on chromosome 22q12.3. This condition has been designated as IMD63 or immunodeficiency 63 with lymphoproliferation and autoimmunity.

IMD66, also known as Immune Deficiency Syndrome 66, is a primary immunodeficiency disease that affects the body's ability to fight off infections. It is caused by mutations in the MKL1 gene on chromosome 22q13.1-q13.2, and can lead to recurrent bacterial infections during infancy. The immune system of an individual with IMD66 has difficulty migrating and chemotaxis primarily in neutrophils, although other cell types may also be affected. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the gene (one from each parent) to develop the disease.

IMD61 is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the immune system, specifically by impairing the ability of B cells to produce antibodies. This condition typically presents in early childhood with recurrent infections due to an intrinsic defect in the ability of B cells to produce antibodies that has a material basis in hemizygous mutation in the SH3KBP1 gene on chromosome Xp22.12. The exact synonym for IMD61 is immunodeficiency 61.

User, it appears that you are asking about information related to immunodeficiency 34. I can confirm that it is a type of X-linked recessive disease, characterized by phagocyte bactericidal dysfunction and increased susceptibility to infection by poorly virulent mycobacteria. It has a material basis in hemizygous mutation in the CYBB gene on chromosome Xp21.1-p11.4, and is also known as AMCBX2, IMD34, X-linked MSMD due to CYBB deficiency, X-linked mendelian susceptibility to mycobacterial diseases due to CYBB deficiency, familial atypical mycobacteriosis X-linked 2, and immunodeficiency 34, mycobacteriosis, X-linked. Is there anything else you would like me to clarify or assist with?

Immunodeficiency 50, also known as X-linked combined immunodeficiency (CID), is a type of genetic disorder that affects the immune system. It is caused by mutations in the MSN gene on the X chromosome and leads to profound lymphopenia, hypogammaglobulinemia, poor immune response to vaccine antigens, fluctuating neutropenia, and recurrent bacterial or varicella zoster virus infections in early childhood. It has exact synonyms such as CID due to Moesin deficiency, IMD50, MSN-related combined immunodeficiency, X-linked Moesin-associated immunodeficiency, and combined immunodeficiency due to Moesin deficiency.

Congenital Disorder Of Glycosylation Type Ii (Immunodeficiency 47) is a primary immunodeficiency disease characterized by liver dysfunction, recurrent bacterial infections, hypogammaglobulinemia, and defective glycosylation of serum proteins that has material basis in hemizygous mutation in the ATP6AP1 gene on chromosome Xq28. It is also known as Immunodeficiency 47 or CDG IIs.

I understand that you have provided information about a specific type of immunodeficiency called Immunodeficiency 71, also known as IMD71 or PLTEID. This condition is characterized by thrombocytopenia, impaired neutrophil and T-cell chemotaxis, impaired T-cell activation, and onset in infancy or early childhood of recurrent infections and inflammatory features. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the ARPC1B gene on chromosome 7q22.1. Additionally, it can be synonymous with other terms such as IMD71, PLTEID, immunodeficiency 71 with inflammatory disease and congenital thrombocytopenia, and platelet abnormalities with eosinophilia and immune-mediated inflammatory disease.

IMD70 is an abbreviation for Immunodeficiency 70, which is a type of autosomal dominant combined T cell and B cell immunodeficiency. It is characterized by decreased CD4+ T cells, decreased CD19+ B cells, recurrent bacterial infections, and severe cutaneous warts on the hands, feet, and face. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the IVNS1ABP gene on chromosome 1q25.3.

Immunodeficiency 69, also known as IMD69, is a type of autosomal recessive disease characterized by T cell and NK cell immunodeficiency. It affects the body's ability to fight off infections, particularly those caused by Mycobacterium tuberculosis. People with this condition have an increased susceptibility to disseminated mycobacterial infection and may also experience a failure of T and NK cells to produce gamma-interferon when stimulated in vitro. The IMD69 gene is located on chromosome 12q15, and mutations in this gene can lead to the condition.

growth hormone secreting pituitary adenoma 2 is a type of growth hormone secreting pituitary adenoma that has the exact synonyms GH-secreting pituitary adenoma 2, PITA2, X-linked acromegaly, and acromegaly due to pituitary adenoma 2. It is characterized by adult-onset sporadic acromegaly and somatic somatotropinoma that has a material basis in mutation in the GPR101 gene on chromosome Xq26.3.

pituitary adenoma 5 is a type of pituitary adenoma that has the definition of being characterized by the development of different types of familial or sporadic pituitary adenomas with a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the CDH23 gene on chromosome 10q22.1. It also has an exact synonym called PITA5, and multiple types can be included within this classification.

Pituitary adenoma 1 is a type of pituitary adenoma, which refers to a benign tumor that develops in the pituitary gland. It has a specific definition as a pituitary adenoma characterized by different types of familial or sporadic pituitary adenomas that have a material basis in heterozygous mutation in AIP on chromosome 11q13.2. Additionally, it has an exact synonym called PITA1 and can be referred to as multiple types of pituitary adenoma.

Pituitary adenoma 3, also known as PITA3, is a type of pituitary adenoma characterized by the development of predominantly GH-secreting pituitary adenomas in some patients. However, it can also include ACTH-secreting adenomas that have a somatic mutation in the GNAS gene on chromosome 20q13.32. This type of pituitary adenoma is considered to be part of multiple types of pituitary adenomas, and it has the material basis in somatic mutation in the GNAS gene.

Mutilating palmoplantar keratoderma with periorificial keratotic plaques is a type of keratosis that affects the skin on the palms and soles of the feet, as well as the surrounding areas. It can cause severe itching and is characterized by thick, scaly patches of skin that can be painful when rubbed or causing discomfort in general. This condition can lead to difficulty walking due to the build-up of keratotic plaques on the soles of the feet. It is also known as Olmsted syndrome, mutilating palmoplantar hyperkeratosis with periorificial keratotic plaques or simply palm and periorificial keratoderma.

x linked mutilating palmoplantar keratoderma with periorificial keratotic plaques is a type of x linked recessive disease.
x linked mutilating palmoplantar keratoderma with periorificial keratotic plaques is a type of mutilating palmoplantar keratoderma with periorificial keratotic plaques.
x linked mutilating palmoplantar keratoderma with periorificial keratotic plaques is a type of something that at least has material basis in some x linked recessive inheritance.

x linked mutilating palmoplantar keratoderma with periorificial keratotic plaques has exact synonym OLMSX.
x linked mutilating palmoplantar keratoderma with periorificial keratotic plaques has exact synonym X-linked Olmsted syndrome.

autosomal dominant mutilating palmoplantar keratoderma with periorificial keratotic plaques is a type of autosomal dominant disease.
autosomal dominant mutilating palmoplantar keratoderma with periorificial keratotic plaques is a type of mutilating palmoplantar keratoderma with periorificial keratotic plaques.
autosomal dominant mutilating palmoplantar keratoderma with periorificial keratotic plaques is a type of something that at least has material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance.
autosomal dominant mutilating palmoplantar keratoderma with periorificial keratotic plaques has definition A mutilating palmoplantar keratoderma with periorificial keratotic plaques that has_material_basis_in heterozygous mutation in the TRPV3 gene on chromosome 17p13.2..
autosomal dominant mutilating palmoplantar keratoderma with periorificial keratotic plaques has exact synonym OLMS1.
autosomal dominant mutilating palmoplantar keratoderma with periorificial keratotic plaques has exact synonym Olmsted syndrome 1.
autosomal dominant mutilating palmoplantar keratoderma with periorificial keratotic plaques has exact synonym autosomal dominant Olmsted syndrome.

Congenital Megabladder is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects the urinary bladder. It is characterized by a massively dilated urinary bladder with disruption of the smooth muscle in the wall of the bladder. This condition has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the MYOCD gene on chromosome 17p12. The condition is also known as MGBL.

Immunodeficiency 72, also known as combined immunodeficiency with autoinflammation, is a type of autosomal recessive disorder that affects the immune system. It usually presents in early childhood and is characterized by recurrent infections or inflammation, susceptibility to both viral and bacterial infections, development of allergies or atopy, liver and spleen enlargement, lymph node swelling, and abnormalities in immune cell populations. The condition is caused by mutations in the NCKAP1L gene on chromosome 12q13.1-q13.2.

Non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 2 (NSXID2) is a type of non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by mild to moderate intellectual disability in males and mild intellectual disability in females. In addition, males with NSXID2 typically have short stature, large head size, prominent ears, and high arched palate. They also tend to have larger testicular volumes compared to their peers.
NSXID2 is caused by mutations in a region on the Xp22.3 chromosome, either homozygous or heterozygous. This disorder has an X-linked dominant inheritance pattern.

This information is provided by SNOMED CT, a comprehensive clinical vocabulary that includes terms such as non syndromic x linked intellectual disability 73. SNOMED CT is used to facilitate accurate and complete medical coded data recording at the point of care. It is designed to support clinicians in accurately documenting diagnoses, interventions and outcomes.

It should be noted that while this information is sourced from a reliable and comprehensive vocabulary, it should always be considered in the context of individual patient presentation and clinical judgment.

Non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 104, also known as MRX104 or X-linked mental retardation 104, is a genetic condition that is characterized by global developmental delay, mild to severe intellectual disability with variable seizures, poor or absent speech, and behavioral problems in males. It has a material basis in hemizygous mutations in the FRMPD4 gene located on the Xp22.2 chromosome.

Non syndromic x linked intellectual disability 19 is a type of non syndromic x linked intellectual disability.
Non syndromic x linked intellectual disability 19 is a type of x linked dominant disease.
Non syndromic x linked intellectual disability 19 is a type of something that at least has material basis in some x linked dominant inheritance.
Non syndromic x linked intellectual disability 19 has definition A non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by mild to moderate intellectual disability that has_material_basis_in hemizygous or heterozygous mutation in the RPS6KA3 gene on chromosome Xp22.12..
Non syndromic x linked intellectual disability 19 has exact synonym MRX19.
Non syndromic x linked intellectual disability 19 has exact synonym X-linked mental retardation 19.<|endoftext|>

Non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability 103, also known as MRX103 and X-linked mental retardation 103, is a type of non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by intellectual disability and facial feature anomalies. It has material basis in hemizygous mutation in the KLHL15 gene on chromosome Xp22.11.

text: This is a description of non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability related to the ARX gene. It is characterized by moderate to profound intellectual disability with variable additional features that have a material basis in hemizygous mutation in the ARX gene on chromosome Xp21.3. This condition has several alternative names, including ARX-related intellectual disability, MRXARX, X-linked mental retardation 29 and others, and is sometimes referred to as X-linked mental retardation 32, 38, 52, or 76. It can also be known as X-linked mental retardation with or without seizures ARX-related.<|end_of_topic|>

non syndromic x linked intellectual disability 21, also known as MRX34 or X-linked mental retardation 21/34, is a type of non-syndromic X-linked intellectual disability. Mayer Rokitansky Kuster Hauser (MRKH) syndrome is a rare genetic disorder characterized by the underdevelopment of the reproductive organs, specifically the uterus and upper part of the vagina. It occurs due to a chromosomal abnormality known as 46,XX testicular DSD (disorders of sex development). In patients with normal secondary sex characteristics and a typical female karyotype (46,XX), MRKH syndrome can cause significant challenges during reproductive life.

This disorder is named after its four discoverers: Mayer Rokitansky, Karl Kuster, Richard Hauser, and Georg Ludwig Hertwig. It primarily affects females, although rare cases have been reported in males. MRKH syndrome can lead to a range of complications such as vaginal atresia, cervical stenosis, and infertility due to the underdevelopment or absence of the reproductive organs.

Treatment options for MRKH syndrome include surgery, hormone therapy, and reconstructive surgeries like uterus transplantation in some cases. However, it is essential to consult a medical professional who specializes in genital and reproductive disorders for the most accurate diagnosis and appropriate treatment plan.

It is important to note that Schinzel Type Phocomelia can be diagnosed in utero through prenatal testing, such as chorionic villus sampling (CVS) or amniocentesis. Early detection and proper medical care can help manage the symptoms of this condition and improve the quality of life for those affected by it.

mismatch repair cancer syndrome is a genetic condition that can cause various types of cancer to develop, especially during childhood. These genes are located on the short arm of chromosome 3 (3p21-p16), as well as on the short arm of chromosome 7 (7p22.1). The condition is usually diagnosed through genetic testing, and treatment typically involves surgery, chemotherapy, and/or radiation therapy.

Microlissencephaly is a rare neurological disorder that affects the development of the brain, causing it to be smaller than normal. It can also cause intellectual disabilities and seizures. The severity of microlissencephaly can vary greatly from one individual to another. In some cases, it may only cause mild symptoms, while in others, it may lead to more significant developmental delays and health issues. There is no cure for microlissencephaly, but early intervention and appropriate care can help individuals with the condition to reach their full potential.

Lissencephaly 4, also known as LIS4, is a type of autosomal recessive brain disorder. It is characterized by severe microcephaly (extreme smallness of the head), profound intellectual disability, and extensive brain atrophy. The condition has a material basis in mutations in the NDE1 gene located on chromosome 16p13.1. Lissencephaly 4 is one of several types of lissencephaly, which are characterized by abnormal cerebral development and a small head size.

Lissencephaly 6, also known as LIS6, is a rare genetic disorder that affects brain development. It is characterized by severe microcephaly (abnormally small head size), lissencephaly (smooth, wrinkled brain surface), pachygyria (a thickening of the cerebral cortex), and hypoplasia of the corpus callosum (underdevelopment of the brain's communication pathway).

Lissencephaly 6 is caused by mutations in the KATNB1 gene, which is located on chromosome 16q21. Homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in this gene can lead to the development of the disorder.

Individuals with Lissencephaly 6 may experience significant developmental delays and intellectual disability. They may also have seizures, feeding difficulties, and other health issues. There is no cure for Lissencephaly 6, but early intervention and proper medical care can help manage the symptoms and improve quality of life.

Lissencephaly is a type of congenital brain abnormality characterized by an abnormally thick cortex and reduced or abnormal lamination. There are different types of Lissencephaly, including Lissencephaly 1, which has a material basis in mutation heterozygous in the PAFAH1B1 gene on chromosome 17p13.3. It is also known by its exact synonyms LIS1 and PAFAH1B1-related lissencephaly.

x linked lissencephaly 2 is a type of lissencephaly, which is characterized by structural brain anomalies, early-onset intractable seizures, severe psychomotor retardation, and ambiguous genitalia. It has a material basis in mutations in the ARX gene on chromosome Xp21.3.
x linked lissencephaly 2 is also known as X-linked lissencephaly with abnormal genitalia, X-linked lissencephaly with ambiguous genitalia, and X-linked lissencephaly-corpus callosum agenesis-genital anomalies syndrome. It is also referred to as XLAG syndrome and XLIS2.

Lissencephaly is a condition characterized by the absence of, or reduction in, cerebral white matter. It can occur due to genetic factors or other causes. There are several types of lissencephaly, including X-linked lissencephaly type 1 (XLIS1), which is caused by a mutation in the doublecortin gene (DCX) on the X chromosome. This condition affects males more severely than females due to the X-linked nature of the gene. Lissencephaly can lead to a range of symptoms, including developmental delay, seizures, and feeding difficulties. In some cases, it can be diagnosed through imaging techniques such as MRI or CT scans. Treatment options may include physical therapy, speech therapy, and medications to manage symptoms.

Leber congenital amaurosis with early onset deafness, also known as LCAEOD, is a type of sensory system disease that affects the eyesight and hearing. It is caused by a genetic mutation in the TUBB4B gene located on chromosome 9q34.3. This condition is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, which means that a person has a 50% chance of inheriting it if one of their parents carries the gene. Symptoms typically appear early in life and can include severe vision and hearing loss, as well as other developmental delays. There is no cure for LCAEOD, but treatments such as vitamin A supplements and cochlear implants may help improve some of its symptoms.

Congenital symmetric circumferential skin creases 2, also known as CSCSC2, is a type of autosomal dominant disease characterized by the presence of multiple benign circumferential skin creases on limbs. Alopecia, neurologic defects, and endocrinopathy syndrome (ANE) is a rare autosomal recessive genetic disorder that affects the hair, brain, and endocrine system. It is characterized by abnormal development of hair follicles resulting in balding, neurological problems such as ataxia and dystonia, and endocrinopathy due to the absence or malfunction of the adrenal gland. The disorder has a genetic basis, with mutations in the RBM28 gene on chromosome 7q32.1 being responsible for its development.

Focal segmental glomerulosclerosis 3 (FSGS3) is a type of autosomal genetic disease that is characterized by the presence of deposits in the mesangial area and the loss of function mutation in the CD2AP gene on chromosome 6p12.3. It has exact synonym FSGS3, which refers to a focal segmental glomerulosclerosis that is caused by a genetic defect in the CD2AP gene. This type of kidney disease can lead to chronic kidney failure and end-stage renal disease if not properly managed. Treatment may include medications to control blood pressure, proteinuria, and swelling, as well as other measures to support overall health.

glutaric acidemia type 3 is a medical condition that affects the body's ability to break down certain amino acids. It is caused by a deficiency in the enzyme glutaryl-CoA oxidase, which is responsible for converting glutarate into another compound called succinate. This can lead to an accumulation of glutaric acid in the body, which can cause various symptoms such as muscle weakness, fatigue, and difficulty walking. glutaric acidemia type 3 is typically inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, meaning that a person must inherit two copies of the gene for it to be expressed. It has also been referred to as glutaric aciduria type 3 or GA III, among other names.

GAPO syndrome is a genetic disorder that affects the growth, hair, teeth and eyes. It is caused by mutations in the ANTXR1 gene and can be inherited in an autosomal recessive manner. Gaucher's disease type IIIc, also known as GD3C, is a type of Gaucher's disease characterized by the presence of cardiovascular calcifications in addition to the typical symptoms of type III. It has a material basis in homozygosity for an asp409-to-his (D409H) mutation in the GBA1 gene on chromosome 1q22. This condition is also known by other names such as Gaucher disease-ophthalmoplegia-cardiovascular calcification syndrome and Gaucher-like disease. Ghosal Hematodiaphyseal Syndrome is a rare autosomal recessive disorder characterized by increased bone density in the diaphyseal region, aregenerative corticosteroid-sensitive anemia, and osteopenia. It is also known as Ghosal Hematodiaphyseal Dysplasia and Ghosal Syndrome, as well as Diaphyseal Dysplasia-Anemia Syndrome.

glutathione synthetase deficiency of erythrocytes is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the red blood cells. It results in hemolytic anemia and a deficiency in glutathione, which is limited to the red blood cells. The nucleated cells are able to maintain normal or near normal expression levels of GSH. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the GSS gene on chromosome 20q11.22. It is also known as glutathione synthetase deficiency without 5-oxoprolinuria.

Hepatic veno-occlusive disease (VOD) with immunodeficiency is a rare genetic disorder that occurs due to mutations in the SP110 gene on chromosome 2q37.1. It is characterized by severe hypogammaglobulinemia, combined T and B cell immunodeficiency, absent lymph node germinal centers, absent tissue plasma cells, hepatic vascular occlusion, and fibrosis. It is also known as VODI (Veno-Occlusive Disease with Immunodeficiency) and hepatic veno-occlusive disease-immunodeficiency syndrome.

Homocystinuria megaloblastic anemia cble type is a rare genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to produce and use methylcobalamin (vitamin B12). It leads to an accumulation of homocysteine, which can damage blood vessels and other tissues in the body. The condition may cause delayed development, low energy levels, abnormal growth, and anemia due to the breakdown of red blood cells. Homocystinuria megaloblastic anemia cble type is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the gene for the disorder (one from each parent). Treatment typically includes dietary changes, vitamin supplements, and medications to manage symptoms.

Homocystinuria megaloblastic anemia cblg type is a rare genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to produce and use methylcobalamin, a form of vitamin B12. It leads to an accumulation of homocysteine, which can damage blood vessels and increase the risk of heart disease and stroke. The disorder also causes megaloblastic anemia, characterized by large red blood cells and hemolytic anemia. Symptoms may include fatigue, weakness, pale skin, depression, irritability, and neurological problems. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the gene to develop the disorder. Treatment typically involves dietary supplements of vitamin B12 and folate, as well as medications to manage symptoms.

hydroxykynureninuria is a type of autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by the accumulation of kynurenine, xanthurenic acid and 3-hydroxykynurenine in the body due to impaired tryptophan metabolism. This results in high urinary excretion of these compounds, which can be detected through a urine test. Hydroxykynureninuria has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the KYNU gene on chromosome 2q22.2. It is also known as kynureninase deficiency and xanthurenic aciduria.

Acetylglutamate synthase deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive disease. It is also classified as a urea cycle disorder, which are genetic conditions that affect the way the body processes ammonia, a byproduct of protein metabolism. Acetylglutamate synthase deficiency specifically refers to a lack of activity of the N-acetyl glutamate synthase enzyme, resulting in the accumulation of ammonia in the blood.
This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the NAGS gene on chromosome 17q21.31. The term "hyperammonemia due to N-acetylglutamate synthase deficiency" is also used to describe this condition.

Leydig cell hypoplasia is a medical condition that affects the development of the reproductive organs in males. It is a form of autosomal recessive disease, which means that it is passed down through generations of a family and can be hidden or mild in expression.
Leydig cell hypoplasia is characterized by underdevelopment of the Leydig cells, which are responsible for producing testosterone. This can result in a lack of development or underproduction of male sex hormones, leading to various physical and functional symptoms.
Leydig cell hypoplasia can also be referred to as 46,XY DSD (Disorders of Sex Development) due to LH resistance or LHB deficiency. It is important for individuals with this condition to receive appropriate medical care and treatment to manage their symptoms and ensure proper development and functioning of their reproductive organs.

Leydig cell hypoplasia type I, also known as 46,XY DSD (disorder of sex development) due to complete LH receptor inactivation, is a condition characterized by low testosterone and high LH levels, lack of responsiveness to LH/CG challenges, absence of breast development, and the absence of secondary male sex characteristics. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous complete inactivation mutations in the LHCGR gene on chromosome 2p16.3.

Leydig cell hypoplasia type II, also known as 46,XY DSD due to partial LH receptor inactivation, is a condition characterized by variable features ranging from micropenis to severe hypospadias and bifid scrotum. This condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous partial inactivation mutations in the LHCGR gene on chromosome 2p16.3. It is important to note that this condition is due to partial luteinizing hormone resistance, and not just a simple Leydig cell hypoplasia.

Leucine-sensitive hypoglycemia of infancy is a rare genetic disorder characterized by recurrent episodes of low blood sugar levels after consuming protein-rich foods or drinks. It is caused by mutations in the SUR1 gene on chromosome 11p15.1, which encodes a subunit of the ATP-sensitive potassium channel involved in regulating glucose metabolism. The condition typically presents in early infancy and can be managed with a low-protein diet and other appropriate measures.

The term "hypoinsulinemic hypoglycemia with hemihypertrophy" refers to a condition that is caused by an inherited metabolic disorder. Another name for this condition is "hypoinsulinemic hypoglycemia and body hemihypertrophy" (HIHGHH).

Woodhouse-Sakati syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects multiple systems of the body. It is caused by mutations in the DCAF17 gene and can cause symptoms such as hypogonadism, alopecia, diabetes mellitus, intellectual deficit, extrapyramidal signs with choreoathetoid movements and dystonia. The syndrome has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the DCAF17 gene on chromosome 2q31.1.
It is also known as Diabetes-hypogonadism-deafness-intellectual disability syndrome, and has other synonyms such as hypogonadism, alopecia, diabetes mellitus, mental retardation, deafness, and extrapyramidal syndrome. It can also be referred to as Progressive extrapyramidal disorder with primary hypogonadism, mental retardation, alopecia.

iminoglycinuria is a type of renal tubular transport disease characterized by impaired renal tube reabsorption of proline, hydroxyproline and glycine and elevated urine levels of the imino acids and glycine. Nephrotic syndrome type 23 is a rare genetic disorder that affects the kidneys. It typically affects children and young adults and is characterized by heavy proteinuria, swelling in the legs and ankles, low levels of albumin in the blood, and abnormalities in the structure and function of the glomeruli (small filters in the kidney that allow water and other substances to pass through). It is caused by mutations in the KIRREL1 gene on chromosome 1q23.1.

Nephrotic syndrome type 21, also known as NPHS21, is a rare form of nephrotic syndrome that primarily affects children. It is an autosomal recessive disorder, which means that it is inherited from both parents and can result in the condition when there is a mutation on one or both copies of the affected gene. The onset of symptoms typically occurs during the first year of life and may include rapidly progressive kidney dysfunction, proteinuria (excessive protein in the urine), and mesangial sclerosis (thickening of the glomerular basement membrane). Diagnosis is made through genetic testing to identify mutations in the AVIL gene on chromosome 12q14.1. Treatment typically includes a combination of medications to manage symptoms and prevent complications, such as high blood pressure and edema.

Nephrotic syndrome type 22 is a genetic kidney disorder that typically affects children and causes damage to the kidneys. It is caused by mutations in the NOS1AP gene, which is located on chromosome 1q23.3. The symptoms of this condition include edema, proteinuria, hypoproteinemia, and microscopic hematuria. It also leads to thickening of the glomerular basement membrane and effacement of podocyte foot processes. This disorder is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner.

Primary Ovarian Insufficiency (POI) is a genetic condition where the ovaries stop functioning properly. It typically affects women in their late 30s or early 40s, causing irregular menstrual cycles and eventually leading to the cessation of menstruation. POI can be caused by various factors such as age, hormonal imbalances, medical conditions, and genetic inheritance.

In the case of Primary Ovarian Insufficiency 18 (POI18), it is a specific type of POI that has a genetic basis. It is characterized by irregular menstrual cycles and cessation of menstruation in the third decade of life, due to homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the C14orf39 gene located on chromosome 14q23.1. POI18 is also known as Premature Ovarian Failure 18 (POF18).

It's important to note that while genetic testing can help identify mutations in the C14orf39 gene, it does not guarantee a diagnosis of POI18. It may simply indicate that a person has an increased risk of developing POI due to their genetic makeup. Treatment options depend on the underlying cause and symptoms, but hormone replacement therapy (HRT) can help regulate menstrual cycles in some cases.

Spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia, also known as SED for short, is a type of autosomal dominant disorder. It affects the development of bones and joints in the body, causing issues such as premature degeneration of joints and abnormalities in the growth of bone structures.
SED is typically passed down through families due to inheritance of a faulty gene from one or both parents. The condition can cause various symptoms, including pain, stiffness, limited movement, and deformities in the affected bones. In some cases, it may also affect the spine and other joints in the body.
Overall, Spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia is a complex condition that requires careful management by healthcare professionals to address its physical, emotional, and social impact on individuals affected by the disorder.

Spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia, also known as SEDK, is a type of autosomal dominant disorder that affects the development of bones in the spine and legs. It is caused by mutations in the ACAN gene on chromosome 15q26.1. The condition causes abnormalities in the growth and development of the spine, leading to short stature and other skeletal abnormalities. Symptoms may include bowed legs, a rounded back, and limited range of motion in the joints. Treatment for SEDK typically involves physical therapy, braces, and pain management.

Spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia tarda is a type of spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia that is characterized by impaired growth of the bones of the spine and the ends of the long bones, which becomes apparent after birth.

Autosomal dominant spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia tarda, also known as ADSPD, is a type of autosomal dominant disease. This means that the condition is passed down through genes from one parent to their offspring. In this case, if one parent has the gene for ADSPD, there is a 50% chance that they will pass it on to their child.

ADSPD affects the development of bones in the spine and lower extremities. It can cause problems with growth and development, as well as pain and stiffness in the joints. Treatment typically focuses on managing symptoms and improving quality of life. There is no cure for ADSPD at this time.

It's important to note that while genetics play a role in developing ADSPD, other factors may also contribute to the development of the condition. If you have concerns about your risk or your child's risk of developing ADSPD, it is recommended to speak with a healthcare professional for further evaluation and advice.

spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia with punctate corneal dystrophy is a type of spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia characterized by the presence of dystrophic punctate calcifications in the full depth of the corneal stroma. The disorder also affects the fingers and toes, resulting in brachydactyly (shortened fingers and toes) and distinctive speech patterns. SED-BDS is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the gene (one from each parent) to develop the disorder. It is also sometimes referred to as Tattoo dysplasia or Fantasy Island syndrome.

Spondylometaphyseal dysplasia is a type of osteochondrodysplasia that affects the vertebrae in the spine and the joints at the ends of the long bones (metaphyses) in the arms and legs. spondylometaphyseal dysplasia, algerian type is a form of spondylometaphyseal dysplasia, characterized by dwarfism, genu valgum deformity, progressive kypho-scoliosis, wrist deformity, myopia and severe metaphyseal dysplasia. spondylometaphyseal dysplasia sedaghatian type is a genetic disorder that affects the development of the bones and joints. It is caused by mutations in the GPX4 gene, which is located on chromosome 19p13.3. Symptoms of spondylometaphyseal dysplasia sedaghatian type include severe metaphyseal chondrodysplasia with mild limb shortening, platyspondyly, delayed epiphyseal ossification, irregular iliac crests, pulmonary hemorrhage, severe hypotonia and cardiorespiratory problems. The disorder has been named after its discoverer, Sedaghatian. It is one of several types of spondylometaphyseal dysplasia, which is a broader category of genetic disorders that affect the development of the bones and joints.

So, in summary, muscular dystrophy dystroglycanopathy is a type of congenital muscular dystrophy characterized by defective glycosylation of dystroglycan. It has exact synonyms such as CMD due to dystroglycanopathy, MDDG, and congenital muscular dystrophy due to dystroglycanopathy.

Muscular dystrophy, dystroglycanopathy type B (MDDGB) is a subtype of muscular dystrophy that is characterized by early onset of muscle weakness, intellectual disability in most cases, and variable presence of mild brain anomalies. It is also known as MDDGB.

Muscular dystrophy, dystroglycanopathy type B15 is a genetic disorder that affects the muscles. It is caused by mutations in the DPM3 gene on chromosome 1q22. The condition is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner. It has been described as having "material basis" in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations of the DPM3 gene.
Muscular dystrophy, dystroglycanopathy type B15 is also known as MDDGB15 and congenital muscular dystrophy DPM3-related.

Muscular Dystrophy, Dystroglycanopathy Type B14 is a type of autosomal recessive disease. It is also referred to as MDDGB14 and congenital muscular dystrophy GMPPB-related. The gene responsible for this condition is located on chromosome 3p21.31, and it can be inherited in either a homozygous or compound heterozygous manner.

Muscular dystrophy, dystroglycanopathy type B3 (MDDGB3) is a form of muscular dystrophy that affects the body's ability to maintain healthy muscle. It is caused by mutations in the POMGNT1 gene on chromosome 1p34.1, which can be inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern. This condition has been also known as congenital muscular dystrophy POMGNT1-related. It is important to note that while this disease has a genetic basis, it does not have a specific cure and treatment focuses on managing symptoms.

Muscular dystrophy, dystroglycanopathy type B4 (MDDGB4) is a genetic disorder characterized by muscle weakness and a lack of intellectual development. It is caused by mutations in the FKTN gene, which is located on chromosome 9q31.2. The condition is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, meaning that to develop the disease, a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene, one from each parent.

Muscular dystrophy, dystroglycanopathy type B2 is a genetic disorder that affects the muscles and is caused by mutations in the POMT2 gene. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that to develop the disease, a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene, one from each parent. The condition is characterized by progressive muscle weakness and can lead to significant disability if left untreated. There is no cure for this condition, but physical therapy, assistive devices, and medications can help manage the symptoms.

Muscular dystrophy, dystroglycanopathy type C12 is a type of autosomal recessive muscle disorder. It has exact synonyms such as LGMD due to POMK deficiency and Limb-girdle muscular dystrophy due to POMK deficiency. It is characterized by limb-girdle congenital muscular dystrophy and cognitive impairment, which has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the POMK gene on chromosome 8p11.21.

Muscular dystrophy, dystroglycanopathy type C8 is a genetic disorder that affects the muscles and can cause intellectual disability and gait abnormalities. It is caused by mutations in the POMGNT2 gene on chromosome 3p22.1. The exact synonyms for this condition include LGMDR24, MDDGC2, autosomal recessive limb-girdle muscular dystrophy 24, and muscular dystrophy-dystroglycanopathy (limb-girdle) type C, 8.

Kinsship syndrome, also known as AFF3-related mesomelic dysplasia or Steichen-Gersdorf type mesomelic dysplasia, is a rare genetic disorder that affects multiple organ systems in the body. It is characterized by developmental delay, intellectual disability, seizures, and a specific set of physical features such as short stature, small hands and feet, and an abnormal shape to the bones of the arms and legs (mesomelic dysplasia). Other common features include horseshoe kidneys, which are a congenital malformation of the kidneys that can cause problems with urine flow, and failure to thrive due to poor growth and development.

Kinsship syndrome is caused by mutations in the AFF3 gene, which is located on chromosome 2q11.2. These mutations can affect the function of a protein called fibroblast growth factor 3 (FGF-3), which plays an important role in brain development and other processes.

There is no cure for Kinsship syndrome, but treatment may help to manage the symptoms. This can include medication to control seizures, physical therapy to improve motor skills and coordination, and nutritional support to promote growth and development. Early intervention and specialized care are essential in managing the complex needs of individuals with this condition.

It is important for families and caregivers to work closely with healthcare professionals to develop an individualized care plan that addresses the unique needs of each person affected by Kinsship syndrome. Support from organizations that focus on genetic disorders can also be beneficial in finding resources and connecting with others who have similar experiences.
Multisystem proteinopathy is a type of motor neuron disease that has a material basis in some inheritance and affects muscle, bone, and the nervous system.

Intestinal infectious disease refers to a type of intestinal infection caused by various pathogens such as viruses, bacteria, fungi, and parasites. Sensorineural hearing loss, also known as high-frequency hearing loss, refers to a type of inner ear disease that results from damage to the cochlea, auditory nerve, and/or brainstem. This can lead to difficulty in hearing sounds at higher frequencies, such as those above 2000 Hz. Sensorineural hearing loss is different from conductive hearing loss, which occurs when there is a problem with the outer or middle ear that prevents sound from reaching the inner ear. It is important to seek medical attention if you experience symptoms of sensorineural hearing loss, as it can be caused by various factors such as exposure to loud noises, certain medications, and age-related changes.

Thyroid lymphoma is a type of cancer that originates in the thyroid gland and involves the spread of abnormal white blood cells, specifically lymphocytes. It is also known as a type of extranodal NK/T cell lymphoma. This type of lymphoma has a distinctive appearance under the microscope and tends to be more aggressive than other types of non-Hodgkin's lymphoma.

Multiple endocrine neoplasia type 2b is a condition that affects the function of hormones in the body. It is characterized by the presence of multiple tumors, including medullary thyroid carcinoma, pheochromocytoma, and intestinal ganglioneuromas. These tumors are benign, but they can cause problems if they become too large or press on other organs. Additionally, people with MEN2B often have a family history of the condition and may experience symptoms such as excessive sweating, rapid heartbeat, and diarrhea. Treatment typically involves surgery to remove the tumors and may also include medications to control hormone levels.

Multiple endocrine neoplasia type 1 (MEN1) is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects multiple endocrine glands in the body. It is characterized by overactive endocrine glands, which can lead to tumors in various organs, including the parathyroid glands, pituitary gland, and pancreas. The disease is caused by a mutation in the MEN1 tumor suppressor gene, which helps regulate normal cell growth and division.

MEN1 can cause tumors in other endocrine glands as well, but it typically affects parathyroid glands more frequently than other organs. The presence of multiple endocrine tumors at the same time is known as MEN 2A or MEN 2B, depending on whether the tumors are functional or non-functional.

Diagnosis of MEN1 typically involves a combination of medical and family history, physical exams, blood tests, and imaging tests such as ultrasounds, CT scans, and MRI scans. Treatment options for MEN1 may include surgery to remove tumors, medications to control hormone levels, and radiation therapy.

In summary, MEN1 is an autosomal dominant disease that affects multiple endocrine glands in the body due to a mutation in the MEN1 gene. It is characterized by overactive endocrine glands and can lead to tumors in various organs. Treatment options may include surgery, medications, and radiation therapy.

Ampulla of Vater cancer can be treated with surgery, chemotherapy, and/or radiation therapy, but the prognosis depends on various factors such as the stage of the cancer, the patient's overall health, and their response to treatment.

Tabes dorsalis is a type of tertiary neurosyphilis, which refers to the slow degeneration of nerve cells and nerve fibers that carry sensory information to the brain. Pelvic inflammatory disease (PID) is a type of bacterial infectious disease that primarily affects the female reproductive system. It is characterized by an infection of the female reproductive organs and can cause pain, fever, and other symptoms. PID is typically caused by the spread of bacteria from the cervix or uterus to the fallopian tubes, ovaries, or surrounding tissues. Pulmonary interstitial emphysema is a type of pulmonary emphysema characterized by the presence of gas in the pulmonary interstitium and lymphatics, usually due to positive pressure ventilation. It is distinguished from other types of emphysema by its location in the interstitium, which is the network of connective tissue that supports the lung's air sacs. This condition can cause shortness of breath and other respiratory symptoms, and may require treatment with medications or oxygen therapy. Compensatory emphysema is a type of pulmonary emphysema that occurs when there is an imbalance in the air sacs within the lungs, often as a result of other lung conditions or surgeries. This can lead to overinflation of certain areas of the lung and difficulty breathing. In some cases, it may also cause chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) exacerbations.

Cycloplegia, also known as ciliary muscle paresis or cycloplegic paralysis of accommodation, is an eye condition that affects the ability of the eye to focus on objects. It occurs when the ciliary muscle, which controls the shape of the lens in the eye, becomes weakened or paralyzed. This can result in difficulty seeing things clearly at different distances and a loss of accommodation, or the ability to change focus from near to far. Cycloplegia is typically diagnosed through a comprehensive eye exam, which may include tests such as the cycloplegic refractive examination, retinoscopy, and autorefraction. Treatment for cycloplegia usually involves correcting any underlying vision problems with glasses or contact lenses, and may also include medications to help improve the function of the ciliary muscle. In some cases, surgery may be recommended to repair or replace damaged eye tissue.

Eye accommodation disease, also known as presbyopia, is a common age-related condition in which the eyes have difficulty focusing on close objects. It occurs when the lens of the eye becomes less flexible, making it harder to change focus from far to near. Symptoms may include blurred vision, difficulty reading, and strain when trying to see up close. Treatment options may include glasses or contact lenses, as well as exercises to help improve eye strength and flexibility.
Asymptomatic neurosyphilis is a type of tertiary neurosyphilis that results in mild meningitis.

Malignant eyelid melanoma is a type of skin cancer that originates from the upper or lower eyelid.

Dysplastic nevus syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by the presence of multiple dysplastic nevi (atypical moles) and a history of melanoma in two family members. Balloon cell malignant melanoma is a type of skin cancer characterized by the presence of large, clear, foamy or finely vacuolated cytoplasm in melanoma cells. It has a distinct appearance when compared to other types of melanoma.

Nodular malignant melanoma is a type of skin cancer that is characterized by its aggressive nature and uniform appearance. It presents as a blue-black, blue-red or amelanotic nodule on the skin. The term "nodular" refers to the growth pattern of the tumor, which appears as a rounded mass rather than as a flat, spread out lesion. This type of melanoma is highly dangerous and can spread quickly if not caught early and treated properly. Endometrial disease is a type of uterine disease that occurs when the tissue lining the uterus (the endometrium) becomes thickened or abnormal. It can be caused by hormonal imbalances, obesity, and other factors. Endometrial hyperplasia, which is an overgrowth of the endometrium, is a common precursor to endometrial cancer. Symptoms may include heavy menstrual bleeding, painful intercourse, and abnormal vaginal bleeding. It is important to consult with a healthcare provider if you experience these symptoms or have concerns about your reproductive health.
Skin amelanotic melanoma is a type of skin cancer that is characterized by the absence or minimal pigmentation in the tumor cells. It is also known as skin amelanotic malignant melanoma.

Subglottis benign neoplasm is a type of laryngeal benign neoplasm that occurs in the subglottic area of the larynx, which is the area just below the vocal cords. It has the same definition as Subglottic tumor and is characterized by the presence of abnormal cells that have grown in an uncontrolled manner. These tumors are generally benign and do not spread to other parts of the body. However, they can cause problems such as breathing difficulties or hoarseness if they grow large enough or obstruct airflow. Larynx leiomyoma is a type of laryngeal benign neoplasm that is derived from smooth muscle cells. It can occur in the supraglottic, glottic, and subglottic regions of the larynx. Larynx leiomyomas are typically slow-growing tumors, but they can become large enough to cause obstruction if left untreated. They are often treated with surgery or laser therapy, depending on the location and size of the tumor.

larynx squamous papilloma is a type of laryngeal benign neoplasm, which means it is a non-cancerous growth in the larynx. hymenolepiasis is a type of parasitic helminthiasis infectious disease that involves infection of the bowel by Hymenolepis nana or Hymenolepis diminuta. The symptoms include diarrhea, gastrointestinal discomfort, itchy anus, poor appetite and weakness.

Cysticercosis is a medical condition that occurs when the eggs or larvae of the Taenia solium tapeworm are ingested, leading to infection in various parts of the body such as the central nervous system, heart, muscles, subcutaneous tissues, and eyes. Sparganosis is a type of parasitic helminthiasis infectious disease that involves the genus Spirometra. It causes cerebral sparganosis, which is characterized by the development of painful nodules in the brain after the plerocercoid larvae have migrated there from the subcutaneous tissue, breast, orbit, urinary tract, pleural cavity, lungs, abdominal viscera, or inner ear. The disease can also affect other organs such as the skin and eyes. It has a broad range of clinical manifestations and can be difficult to diagnose due to its non-specific symptoms. Sparganosis is treated with anti-parasitic medication and surgery if necessary.

Syphilitic encephalitis is a type of encephalitis that occurs as a result of infection with the Treponema pallidum bacterium. It can be transmitted through various means, including contact transmission and congenital transmission from infected mothers to their babies. Gastric leiomyoma is a type of gastrointestinal system benign neoplasm that is characterized by the presence of spindle cells with cigar-shaped nuclei, interlacing fascicles, and a whorled pattern. It has the exact synonym leiomyoma of the stomach.

Intracranial abscess is a type of central nervous system disease that refers to the presence of pus or infected material within the skull, which is part of the central nervous system. This condition can cause a range of symptoms and complications, including headaches, fever, and seizures. In some cases, intracranial abscesses may require surgical intervention to drain the infection and prevent further damage to the brain.

Sleeping sickness, also known as African trypanosomiasis, is a disease caused by the Trypanosoma brucei and gambiense parasites, which are transmitted through the bite of infected tsetse flies (Glossina spp). Symptoms typically include fever, headache, joint pain, itching, confusion, sensory disturbances, poor coordination, and sleep disturbances. If left untreated, sleeping sickness can be fatal. Early diagnosis and treatment are crucial for effective management of the disease.

Tryptanosomiasis is a type of parasitic infection caused by the Trypanosoma protozoan. It can affect both animals and humans, and it is typically transmitted through the bite of an infected insect, such as a tsetse fly or horsefly. The symptoms of tryptanosomiasis may include fever, fatigue, swelling of the lymph nodes, and skin rash. In some cases, it can also lead to more severe complications such as organ failure and death. Treatment typically involves antiparasitic medications and supportive care to manage symptoms and prevent further spread of the disease.

Cerebral artery occlusion, also known as a stroke or brain attack, is a condition in which the blood flow to the brain is disrupted. This can be caused by a blockage in one of the cerebral arteries or a clot that travels through the bloodstream and gets stuck in another part of the brain. Cerebral artery occlusion can lead to serious consequences, including physical and cognitive impairments, depending on the location and severity of the blockage.
It is important for individuals who experience symptoms such as sudden weakness or numbness on one side of their body, difficulty speaking or understanding speech, severe headache, dizziness, or loss of balance to seek immediate medical attention. Early diagnosis and treatment are crucial for minimizing the risk of long-term damage from cerebral artery occlusion.

That is correct. Venous insufficiency, also known as peripheral venous insufficiency, is a condition where the veins in the legs and feet do not return blood effectively to the heart. This can lead to swelling, pain, and other symptoms. There are several causes of venous insufficiency, including age-related factors, injury or surgery to the veins, and certain medical conditions such as deep vein thrombosis (DVT). Treatment options include compression stockings, exercise, and surgical procedures such as vein stripping or endovenous laser therapy.

Psychologic vaginismus is a type of psychosexual disorder that affects women. It occurs when there is an involuntary spasm of the outer muscles of the vagina during penetration, which results from a psychological cause. This means that the problem is not physical but rather emotional or psychological in nature.
Psychologic vaginismus can be caused by a variety of factors including anxiety, fear, guilt, and past trauma. It is important for women who experience this disorder to seek help from a mental health professional as it can lead to feelings of shame, self-esteem issues, and relationship problems.
There are several treatment options available for psychologic vaginismus including therapy, pelvic floor exercises, and medication. The goal of treatment is to address the underlying psychological causes and help the woman regain control over her body and sexual functioning. With proper treatment, most women who suffer from psychologic vaginismus can overcome this disorder and have a fulfilling sex life.

Psychosexual disorders are a group of sexual health disorders that are characterized by a dysfunction in the psychological or emotional aspect of sex, rather than a physical problem. These disorders can affect an individual's ability to experience sexual pleasure, desire, arousal, and orgasm. Examples of psychosexual disorders include:

* Dyspareunia (painful intercourse)
* Hypoactive Sexual Desire Disorder (low libido or decreased interest in sex)
* Orgasmic Disorder (the inability to achieve orgasm)
* Premature Ejaculation (ejaculating too quickly)
* Retarded Ejaculation (delayed ejaculation)
* Sexual Aversion Disorder (a persistent aversion to sexual contact with one's partner)

It is important to note that psychosexual disorders can be caused by various factors, including physical health conditions, medications, hormonal imbalances, past trauma, stress, and relationship issues. It is also worth noting that these disorders are often treatable with the help of a mental health professional or sex therapist.

Conjunctival degeneration, also known as posterior subcapsular cataract, is a type of eye disease that affects the conjunctiva, which is the thin transparent tissue that covers the white part of the eye. Thymus lymphoma, also known as thymic carcinoma or thymosarcoma, is a rare and aggressive type of cancer that arises from the thymus gland. The thymus is an organ located in the chest behind the sternum, which plays a crucial role in the development and maturation of T cells, a type of white blood cell.

Thymus lymphoma typically presents with symptoms such as chest pain, shortness of breath, coughing up blood, hoarseness, and fatigue. It can also cause swelling or a feeling of fullness in the neck or chest, as well as night sweats. The cancer may spread to nearby lymph nodes, as well as to other parts of the body such as the lungs, brain, liver, or bone marrow.

The exact cause of thymus lymphoma is not fully understood, but it is believed to be related to exposure to radiation or certain chemicals. The risk factors for developing this type of cancer include a history of radiation therapy, exposure to certain chemicals such as those found in the rubber industry, and a weakened immune system caused by conditions like HIV/AIDS or organ transplantation.

The diagnosis of thymus lymphoma is typically made through a combination of medical history, physical examination, imaging tests such as chest X-rays or CT scans, and biopsy. Treatment options may include surgery to remove the cancerous thymus gland, radiation therapy, chemotherapy, immunotherapy, and targeted therapy.

In summary, thymus lymphoma is a rare and aggressive type of cancer that arises from the thymus gland. It presents with symptoms such as chest pain, shortness of breath, coughing up blood, hoarseness, and fatigue. The exact cause is not fully understood, but it is believed to be related to exposure to radiation or certain chemicals. Treatment options may include surgery, radiation therapy, chemotherapy, immunotherapy, and targeted therapy.

Endobronchial lipoma is a type of lipoma that occurs within the lumen of a bronchus. It can also be referred to as a bronchial benign neoplasm, which is a non-cancerous growth in the airways. Skin lipoma is a type of skin benign neoplasm, which means it is a non-cancerous growth that arises in the skin. It is also known as cutaneous lipomatous tumor and lipoma of face.

Osteomyelitis is a type of bone inflammation disease that can be caused by either bacterial or fungal infections. It occurs when the infection spreads to the bone or bone marrow, causing pain and swelling in the affected area. Osteomyelitis has a material basis in some bacteria and is characterized by an inflammation of the bone tissue. It can be treated with antibiotics if caused by bacterial infection and antifungal medications if caused by fungal infection.

Liver lipoma is a type of lipoma that occurs in the liver. It is also known as hepatic lipoma or lipoma of the liver. It is a benign neoplasm, which means it is a growth that is not cancerous but can still cause problems if it becomes large enough to press against other organs or structures in the body. It typically develops due to an excess of fat cells in the liver, which can occur for various reasons such as genetics, obesity, or certain medications. The exact synonyms for liver lipoma are "lipoma of the liver" and "hepatic lipoma."
Pleomorphic lipoma is a type of lipoma characterized by the presence of floret giant cells with overlapping nuclei.
